## Architecture

Layered Clean Architecture, organised in **vertical slices** (one folder per
feature, each with its own `domain/`, `data/`, `presentation/`).

```
lib/
├── main.dart
├── bootstrap.dart              Pre-runApp init (env, DI, backend, error zone)
├── app.dart                    MaterialApp.router + global providers
├── core/                       Cross-cutting kernel
│   ├── di/                     get_it + injectable (env-scoped registration)
│   ├── env/                    AppEnv (dev | demo | prod) from --dart-define
│   ├── error/                  Failure sealed hierarchy + error mapper
│   ├── extensions/             context.colors, context.l10n, context.mq
│   ├── logging/                Talker wrapper
│   ├── network/                ConnectivityService
│   ├── payments/               RevenueCat wrapper + entitlement interface
│   ├── router/                 go_router declarative
│   ├── theme/                  AppTheme, AppColors, AppTypography
│   ├── time/                   Clock (inject; never raw DateTime.now())
│   └── widgets/                Shared widgets
└── features/
    ├── _template/              Reference skeleton — copy for new features
    └── <feature_name>/
        ├── data/
        │   ├── datasources/
        │   ├── dtos/
        │   ├── repositories/   real repository impls (dev + prod)
        │   └── fakes/          optional in-memory seeded fakes (demo flavor)
        ├── domain/{entities, repositories, usecases}/
        └── presentation/{blocs, pages, widgets}/
```

### Layer rules

- `domain/` — **pure Dart.** Must NOT import: `flutter/*`, Firebase,
  drift, data layer, presentation layer.
- `data/` — infrastructure. May import: own feature's `domain/`, `core/`.
  DTOs own JSON serialization. Repository impls map infra errors → `Failure`.
- `presentation/` — Flutter. May import: own feature's `domain/`, `core/`.
  **Must NOT** import `data/`.

### Hard rules

- **No `BuildContext` in events.** Side effects via `BlocListener`.
- **No `setState()` inside `build()`.** Ever.
- **Use `MediaQuery.sizeOf(context)`** — never `MediaQuery.of`.
- **Inject `Clock`** (`core/time/clock.dart`). Never raw `DateTime.now()`.
- **All `StreamSubscription`, `*Controller`, `FocusNode`** must be disposed.
- **All Firestore queries:** `.where('ownerId', isEqualTo: uid)` + `.limit(...)`.
- **All multi-doc writes:** `WriteBatch` or `runTransaction`.
- **BLoCs screen-scoped via `BlocProvider(create:)` by default.**
- **Every BLoC overrides `close()`** if it holds subscriptions.
- **Every paid feature is gated through `SubscriptionBloc`** (entitlement check)
  — never read a purchase SDK directly from a widget or feature Bloc.
- **Emulator wiring lives ONLY under the `dev` environment guard** in
  `bootstrap.dart`. Flag it anywhere else.
- **Dev bootstrap fails fast** when the emulators are unreachable — health-check
  the hub first; never hang into a white screen.
- **The `dev` flavor never points at a real Firebase project** — `demo-*`
  project IDs only.
- **Fakes are optional.** Add one under the `demo` environment where the
  emulator can't simulate a state (offline mode, injected errors) or for
  instant backend-free demos.

### Performance rules

- `const` everywhere it compiles.
- Lazy lists only (`ListView.builder`, `SliverList`).
- Heavy work (>16 ms — one 60 fps frame) in isolates.
- `BlocSelector` / `buildWhen` for any state with >3 fields.
- Extract any `build` method >150 lines into a separate widget class.

## Flavors: dev (emulators) · demo (fakes) · prod

Every backend dependency sits behind a repository interface. Three environments,
selected via `--dart-define=APP_ENV=<env>`:

- **`dev`** (default for development) — the **real** Firebase repository impls
  pointed at the **local Firebase Emulator Suite** (`useAuthEmulator`,
  `useFirestoreEmulator`, …), wired only under the dev env in `bootstrap.dart`.
  Uses project ID `demo-<app>` — the Emulator Suite treats `demo-*` projects as
  offline-only, so **no real Firebase project is needed**: a hand-written
  `FirebaseOptions` with projectId `demo-<app>` and dummy keys suffices
  (`flutterfire configure` isn't needed until the backend pass).
- **`demo`** (optional) — in-memory, **seeded** fakes in `data/fakes/`.
  Recommended where the emulator can't simulate a state (offline mode, injected
  errors) and for instant backend-free demos. Not mandatory per repository.
- **`prod`** — the real Firebase project. Used by the **Backend integration
  pass** plan step (against a STAGING project) and release builds.

```bash
# Run the dev flavor (emulators) — used for all simulator verification:
flutter run --dart-define=APP_ENV=dev -d <device>
```

Wiring (via `injectable` environments):

```dart
@Environment('prod')   // dev reuses these prod impls
@LazySingleton(as: AuthRepository)
class FirebaseAuthRepository implements AuthRepository { … }

@Environment('demo')
@LazySingleton(as: AuthRepository)
class FakeAuthRepository implements AuthRepository { … }   // seeded users
```

The dev env reuses the prod impls; `bootstrap.dart` redirects the Firebase SDKs
at the emulators **before** DI resolves anything:

```dart
if (env == AppEnv.dev) {
  // Health-check first — fail fast if the Emulator Suite is down.
  await Firebase.initializeApp(options: demoProjectOptions); // demo-<app> ID
  await FirebaseAuth.instance.useAuthEmulator('localhost', 9199);
  FirebaseFirestore.instance.useFirestoreEmulator('localhost', 8181);
}
```

Rules:
- **Fail fast:** dev bootstrap health-checks the emulator hub
  (`curl http://localhost:4441`) before any `use*Emulator` call. If unreachable,
  throw with a clear "start the emulators" message immediately — never hang
  `runApp()` into a white screen.
- **Non-default ports** in `firebase.json` (defaults collide with other tools —
  never 8080):

  | Emulator | UI | Hub | Auth | Firestore | Database | Storage |
  |---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
  | Port | 4040 | 4441 | 9199 | 8181 | 9100 | 9299 |

- **Seed strategy:** start with
  `--import .firebase/seed --export-on-exit .firebase/seed` so seed data
  round-trips; `.firebase/seed/` is committed.
- `firebase.json`, `.firebaserc`, `firestore.rules`, and
  `firestore.indexes.json` are written directly (no interactive
  `firebase init`) and live in the repo from early development — the emulator
  exercises the security rules continuously.
- When demo fakes exist, seed them with representative data covering each
  screen state (populated, empty, error, offline) and entitlement state (free,
  subscribed, expired), with toggleable failures for edge paths.
- Inspect emulator state via the Firebase MCP where it supports emulators
  (`firestore_query_collection` has `use_emulator`; RTDB tools accept emulator
  URLs; Auth tools are live-only) — otherwise via the emulators' REST endpoints
  with `curl`.
- The real backend is exercised by the **Backend integration pass** plan step
  (staging project) and the human's `HUMAN_SETUP.md` items — never during
  day-to-day development.

### Monetization (RevenueCat)

- Entitlements via `purchases_flutter` (RevenueCat), exposed through
  `core/payments/` and consumed only via `SubscriptionBloc`.
- **iOS simulator:** purchases are testable with a StoreKit configuration file
  (`ios/*.storekit`) — purchase, restore, subscribe, expire — no App Store
  Connect needed. Enable it in the Runner scheme.
- **Android & cross-platform:** `FakePurchaseRepository` (demo flavor) covers
  paywall, gating, restore, upgrade/downgrade, and expiry on the emulator.
- A **Restore Purchases** action is mandatory (App Store requirement).

## Responsive & render-safety

**Zero render (overflow) errors on any size is a hard requirement.** Every
content-bearing layout uses flex (`Expanded`/`Flexible`/`Wrap`/`FittedBox`) and
`LayoutBuilder` / `MediaQuery.sizeOf` — never fixed pixel sizes — and must
survive the **size matrix**:

| Platform | Smallest | Typical | Largest | Tablet |
|----------|----------|---------|---------|--------|
| iOS | iPhone SE | iPhone 16 Pro | iPhone 16 Pro Max | iPad |
| Android | small phone AVD | Pixel-class | — | tablet AVD |

…each at **textScale 1.0 and 2.0**.

Every top-level screen carries an **overflow-guard** widget test. A `RenderFlex`
overflow throws in debug, so pumping at each matrix size and asserting no
exception catches it deterministically. The widget-test matrix is intentionally
stricter than the simulator device set — the 320-wide entry stress-tests below
any current device:

```dart
const _matrix = <Size>[
  Size(320, 568), // narrow stress (below any current device)
  Size(375, 667), // iPhone SE 3rd gen
  Size(402, 874), // iPhone 16 Pro
  Size(440, 956), // iPhone 16 Pro Max
  Size(834, 1194), // iPad
];

for (final size in _matrix) {
  for (final scale in const [1.0, 2.0]) {
    testWidgets('HomeScreen no overflow @ $size x$scale', (tester) async {
      tester.view.physicalSize = size;
      tester.view.devicePixelRatio = 1.0;
      addTearDown(tester.view.resetPhysicalSize);
      await tester.pumpWidget(MediaQuery(
        data: MediaQueryData(size: size, textScaler: TextScaler.linear(scale)),
        child: const _Harness(child: HomeScreen()),
      ));
      expect(tester.takeException(), isNull);
    });
  }
}
```

## Tech stack

> This stack is the project's **explicit override** of the State Management,
> Dependency Injection, and Logging defaults in `docs/flutter-rules.md` (which
> otherwise defaults to built-in state management + manual constructor DI +
> `dart:developer`'s `log`). All other rules in that document apply as written.

- **State:** `flutter_bloc` + sealed states via `freezed`.
- **Models:** `freezed` + `json_serializable`.
- **Routing:** `go_router` (declarative; deep links).
- **DI:** `get_it` + `injectable` (env-scoped: `dev` | `demo` | `prod`).
- **Local DB:** `drift` (compile-time SQL).
- **Backend:** <Firebase / Supabase / none>
- **Payments:** `purchases_flutter` (RevenueCat); fakes + `.storekit` for sims.
- **Logging:** `talker_flutter`.
- **App icon / splash:** `flutter_launcher_icons`, `flutter_native_splash`.
- **Lints:** `very_good_analysis`.
- **Testing:** `bloc_test`, `mocktail`, `integration_test` (run on simulators
  against the `dev` flavor + local Firebase Emulator Suite).

